<DOC><DOCNO> AP890611-0083 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1815EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-India-USTrade     06-11 0176</FIRST><SECOND>BC-India-US Trade,0182</SECOND><HEAD>India Will Not Negotiate on U.S. Trade Act</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   India will not negotiate with the UnitedStates over its citation for violating the U.S. Omnibus Trade Act,under which New Delhi faces retaliatory tariffs for what Washingtoncalls unfair trade laws, Press Trust of India reported.   The news agency on Saturday quoted unidentified governmentofficials as saying that negotiations on trade could not be heldunder threat of retaliation.   Last month, Washington cited India under section 301 of the 1988trade act for impeding direct foreign investment and closing theIndian insurance market to foreign companies. The law allows theUnited States to impose tariffs of 100 percent on goods from Indiaif negotiations fail to remove the barriers within 18 months.   Washington had suggested that negotiations to remove the barriersbegin not later than June 16.   The United States is India's largest trading partner and two-waytrade between the nations was about $5.7 billion in 1988. India helda trading surplus of about $700 million dollars.</TEXT></DOC>